metadata.name: Symphony of fxhash #2
metadata.description:
"Symphony of fxhash" is an animated work that tries to convey feelings.
There are 10 albums in this work. The owners of the albums are the artists who had the most marketplace during the last 7 days.
Each album has about 5 tracks. These tracks are the last 5 works of the artists of the album (there are also artists who had less than 5 works, in this case all their works are included).

metadata.name: Wormhole #25
metadata.description:
wormhole, solution of the field equations in German-born physicist Albert Einstein's theory of general relativity that resembles a tunnel between two black holes or other points in space-time. Such a tunnel would provide a shortcut between its end points
-------------------
Based on my new interest in physics, I decided to use modeling and algorithms to represent wormholes.
In this work, 7 main types of modeling for wormholes are shown.

metadata.name: JAN. 27 #19

This work is related to the announcement of Genuary 32nd.
The challenge that was stated for January 27 is to create a work in the style of Hilma_af_Klint.
a Swedish artist and mystic whose paintings are considered among the first abstract works known in Western art history.
--------------------
In this work, the goal was to prepare a work suitable for the challenge of January 27, inspired by the work of "The swan" by Hilma , also many of colors are taken from Hilma's works.

metadata.name: Step by Step #82
metadata.description:
Step by Step explores the feeling of being stuck, confined - walking the path ahead of you often only seeing the immediate next step until exhaustion. We all feel this way from time to time — in our lives, jobs, bodies, situations — yet in our search for something, we shouldn't forget that there can still be beauty along the path.

The project takes some inspiration from Henri Matisse, both in the aesthetics of his later works (i.e. the "Cut Outs") and metaphorically in the sense that he had underwent medical treatment which left him wheelchair- or bed-bound towards the later part of his life, forcing him to give up painting, yet in his exploration of this new creative medium which involved cutting paper and pinning them up, his unorthodox work went on to become the most transformative of his career.

Released as part of the 4th edition of the Cure³ Parkinson's cure fundraiser exhibition organized by Artwise Curators and Bonhams as part of a specially comissioned selection of generative artists minting NFTs, curated by Foteini Valeonti and Alex Estorick with the support of fx(hash) at Bonhams, London from 13-17th January 2023.

---
33% of primary sales and 3% of secondary sales will be donated on-chain to Cure Parkinson’s
---

Controls:
• 'R' regenerates the piece (e.g. in case the window size changes)

Made in p5js
Created Jan 2023
Artist: Yazid

metadata.name: #2023Streams #136
metadata.description:
#2023Streams is a color theory study that explores the use of algorithmically-generated color palettes and the juxtaposition of color harmonies keyed on a common hue. It brings playfulness to experimentation through the use of randomized features that control lighting, color assortment, and more, to create interesting, vibrant compositions.

I consider this piece—my generative "genesis"—to be a preliminary "sketch" whose desired outcomes are insights into color and light that might be applied to more advanced projects in the future.

This piece is also a first step for me, into the world of professional art. An art school dropout and software engineer by profession, I've been hacking on generative art projects, games, and interactive experiences for more than two decades. But now, in 2023, it's my time to focus and prioritize art and creativity.

Each image can be modified using the following keyboard commands:
- [d] Download the rendered image
- [j] Toggle between "jungle" (dimensional) and "jazz" (flat) modes
- [l] Toggle between light and dark backgrounds
- [e] Toggle between curved (ellipse) and flat (rectangle) shapes
- [s] Enable/disable shadows and highlights
- [t] Enable/disable transparency

Each image is rendered at 2400 x 2400 pixels by default. This should be suitable for an 8" x 8" output (at 300 dpi). Should you desire a higher resolution output, the image can be magnified up to 6x by clicking the "open ↗️" link and appending a density parameter to the URL, e.g. `&density=4` 

Lastly, #2023Streams is licensed under a Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International license. This license allows reusers to distribute, remix, adapt, and build upon the material in any medium or format, so long as attribution is given to the creator. The license allows for commercial use.

What does this license mean? It means I invite you to have fun with your new piece, get creative and bring something new into the world.

I hope you enjoy these outputs as much as I do. Thank you for stopping by—and hopefully collecting.

Ya boy, wut!

metadata.name: <iframes> #9
metadata.description:
The <iframe> HTML element is an element that allows a web document to embed the contents of another web document within itself. iframes are at the core of fxhash. They are portals opening our view to rich content.

This work is a portal to itself. It loads itself within itself 20 times. It's not pretty, it reminds us of WordArt, it's a little bit hacky, it might break when our tools to display HTML will change. But it's a proof that the limits of our tools are only limits until creativity breaks them.

This work is not purely deterministic, because it simply cannot be. Slight timing differences due to loading times being different each time an <iframe> is loaded will make each visualization slightly unique.

If you view this token on mobile, the nesting limit was reduced to 4 to prevent performance issues.

This work is highly experimental. It leverages a "hack" to allow iframes to be nested.
Firefox max <iframe> nesting depth as of 28/12/2021 is capped at 9.
Works with chrome desktop 96.0.4664.110

metadata.name: Perpendicular Inhabitation #461
metadata.description:
'Perpendicular Inhabitation' is a generative collection exploring the relationship between the urban landscape and the human experience, particularly feelings of nostalgia and more specifically 'anemoia' : the feeling of nostalgia for a time or place that we may not have actually experienced first hand. 

Despite depicting a stylised modern architectural language, at its core the collection serves as a homage to 1980s Japan, an era of unprecedented prosperity that left a lasting impression on the music and artwork of the time. Through the use of carefully created palettes and composition, the outputs intend to evoke feelings of optimism, while guiding viewers to consider why the essence of this era is so alluring in the present day as it continues to influence and inspire contemporary art.

The use of exaggerated perpendicular verticals, as well as the heavily foreshortened mountain ranges present in some outputs, convey a sense of hope and possibility for the future. What does it feel like to hope and dream in the city? To look up and be filled with a sense of wonder from the built environment around you?

This project has been created with print in mind at a ratio of 3:4

It is recommended to examine your outputs at full size in order to enjoy them to the fullest.

You are encouraged to return often to notice things you may not have seen previously.

Generated with code using p5.js

Images are generated at 2400 x 3200 px. 

To save a PNG file, please press 'S'.

Depending on the complexity of each output, please wait up to 10 seconds for the image generation to complete.
